The Patterns of the Slopes

Skiers and riders, you’ve all seen these trail maps—they’re essential for navigating the mountain, finding the fastest lift, or planning your next epic run.

In particular, this map, beautifully painted by the legendary James Niehues, is of the South Face of Big Sky, Montana.

But have you ever wondered how common south-facing slopes are? In other words, do most ski trails in this hemisphere favor southern exposure, or are they more often found on the north side of the mountain?

We began our journey to answer this question by gathering data from OpenSkiMap, which refines OpenStreetMap  to create an amazing interactive visualization of the world and all its ski trails.

Thousands of OpenStreetMap contributors have worked for decades to annotate ski areas and their trails.

In this New Hampshire/Vermont region, …

… you can see the iconic Killington and its neighbor Pico.

Here is a local favorite, Whaleback Mountain.

Analyzing this data, we could see how much north-facing each ski area is by looking at its “ski rose”.

Take, for example, Dartmouth Skiway in Lyme, NH.

These are the two signature sides of the Skiway, Holt’s Ledge and Winslow Ledge.

On powder days, from Winslow, you can ski across the road and glide right to the bottom of Holt’s Ledge Double.

If we:

  • gather the coordinates for all trail segments,
  • connect the dots,
  • treat each of these segments as a vector, and
  • scale the vectors by their vertical drops,

we can summarize them in a …

… ski rose!

Similar to how wind roses chart wind speed and direction at a location, ski roses characterize the directions of all trail segments at a ski area.

Each spoke of the circular chart represents a compass direction, with its length proportional to the total length and vertical drop of trail segments in that direction.

Highlighted is the Northwest by West spoke…

… to which these particular segments contribute.

And here’s the North North East spoke.

While these NNE segments may seem small, their verticals contribute to a significantly larger spoke in the rose compared to others.

We can do this for other ski areas too!

Here are 48 more roses. What do you think? Do most of them look north-facing to you?

Our analysis of the slopes of all ski areas across the globe revealed a clear poleward and slight eastward bias.

In other words, the majority of slopes in the northern hemisphere oriented toward the north and east, while those in the southern hemisphere are oriented toward the south and east.

This trend likely reflects the desire to maximize snow retention and minimize sun exposure, ensuring better skiing conditions and longer seasons.

In addition to trail bearings, we have published data on other key metrics of a ski area like total verts, number of lifts, and peak elevations for ski areas across the world.
